ht|i|fp|2|at|^h@2^*BResponding to a weak 2-bid:^*N|fp||at|
^i@21. Possession of 13 points is no big deal; partner has fewer than 13. If you don't have at least 3-card support, and you have 13 HCP or fewer, ^*BYou should Pass partner's weak two-bid^*N.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

^i@22. Support with support.^*N You don't need points to raise partner. Surely, most of my readers have heard of the LAW of Total Tricks (LAW). |
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

^h@2^*BMM^*N: If you have not heard of it, please study the LAW tutorial by Howard at:
|CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.bridgesights.com/hondobridge/hondoviewer/hondoviewer.php?sf=lott^*N|CP||ht|q|AT|^bor the article by Larry at: |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/BridgeArticles/ArticleDetails.aspx?articleID=229^*N|CP||AT|)|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

^C@23.With 3 trumps, raise partner's weak two to the 3-level (if you don't have game interest). ^*N|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT|

^C@24. With 4 trumps, raise to the 4-level. To read all the why's and why-not's, click here. |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/bridge-learning-center/detail/129^*N|CP||
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

^C@25. With an invitational hand, responder should bid 2NT to ask opener if he is minimum or not. Opener rebids his suit with a minimum; with more he identifies his outside Feature (usually an A or K). This is called "Feature." |CP|1|AT|^*hhttps://www.larryco.com/bridge-learning-center/detail/456^*N|CP||AT|. There are a small minority of players who use a different conventional response to the 2NT bid, typically Ogust.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

^C@26.New suits by responder'forcing is Standard. Make sure you agree with your partner.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


