qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      RESPONDING TO WEAK 2-BIDS - FEATURE
      Larry Cohen - Date of publish: 8/1/2014 - Level: Intermediate    
}^-|cs||fp||va|6|AT|^B@2^*BMM: ^*NIn his earlier version of responding to Weak two Bids, Larry had a much longer explanation for "^*BFEATURE^*N" which he omitted in the recent version. Therefore, because many play feature, we decided to re-produce it here following the older version. Some of the examples are repeats. Feature is first.|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|This popular convention is used after your partner opens with a weak two-bid. 

After a 2@D, 2@H, or 2@S weak two-opener a response of 2NT is conventional. A small percentage use it as "Ogust," but most common is "Feature."  The 2NT bidder has at least game (maybe slam) interest. As to what might constitute "interest," see "The Rule of 17." |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/bridge-learning-center/detail/455^*N|CP||
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


AT|

A "Feature" is usually an ^*Bace^*N or ^*Bking^*N. It is never a singleton or void. Occasionally, it can be a queen or even a jack with length.

Here are the responses to the 2NT inquiry:

^CRebid of the Weak-2 suit: ANY MINIMUM (might actually have a "feature" as well).

^CRebid in a new suit: ANY NON-MINIMUM, with a "feature" in the suit bid. 

^CRebid of 3NT: NON-MINIMUM with a "solid" suit.|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


AT|

These responses will be clarified with next examples.|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%example  F1
st||pn|You,,Partner|md|1SQ J T 9 8 3HK 3D5 4C6 4 2,,,|sv|O|rh||ah|FEATURE|ah|Larry Cohen - Example F1|mb|2Sp2np|lb|*bWhat do you respond after 2N?^^3S|mb|3S|NT|^B@2
Rebid 3@S because this is a minimum. Do not show a Feature with a minimum.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT||
%%example F2 
st||pn|You,,Partner|md|1SK Q J 9 8 7HK 5 2D5 4C3 2,,,|sv|O|rh||ah|FEATURE|ah|Larry Cohen - Example F2|mb|2Sp2np|lb|*bWhat do you respond after 2N?^^3H|mb|3H|NT|^B@2
Rebid 3@H to show the heart feature (and extras--not minimum).|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT||
%%example F3 
st||pn|You,,Partner|md|1SK Q 9 8 7 2H7DK 5 4C4 3 2,,,|sv|O|rh||ah|FEATURE|ah|Larry Cohen - Example F3|mb|2Sp2np|lb|*bWhat do you respond after 2N?^^3S|mb|3S|NT|^B@2
You must decide if this is a minimum (in which case rebid 3@S) or a non-minimum (in which case rebid 3@D to show the feature). This could depend on your preempting style (is it a maximum for YOU?). |
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Also important is position and vulnerability. For a 2nd seat Vulnerable preempt, I'd consider this a minimum and would rebid 3@S. For a dealer favorable-vulnerability preempt, I'd consider it a maximum and would rebid 3@D.|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||
%%example  F4
st||pn|You,,Partner|md|1SA K J T 9 7H3 2DQ 4C7 6 4,,,|sv|O|rh||ah|FEATURE|ah|Larry Cohen - Example F4|mb|2Sp2np|lb|*bWhat do you respond after 2N?^^3N|mb|3N|NT|^B@2
I would rebid 3NT and treat this as a "solid suit." Sure, I'd prefer to have AKQ--but I can't treat this as a minimum, and prefer not to announce a diamond feature with only Q4 doubleton.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||
%%example F5 
st||pn|You,,Partner|md|1SA Q T 8 7 6H3DQ J 7 6C4 2,,,|sv|O|rh||ah|FEATURE|ah|Larry Cohen - Example F5|mb|2Sp2np|lb|*bWhat do you respond after 2N?^^3d|mb|?|NT|^B@2
I recommend 3@D to show a non-minimum and a diamond feature. Yes, a feature is usually a king or ace, but what choice do you have?|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


NT|^B@2
You can't rebid 3@S as that would show a minimum. You can't rebid 3NT as that would show a better spade suit. You can't rebid 3@H, because shortness is not a feature.|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


NT||BT||
