qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      RESPONDING TO WEAK 2-BIDS - Notes
      After Partner Responds 2NT to our Weak 2-Bid    }
^-|cs||fp||va|4|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|There is some judgment involved (especially depending on what your partnership considers a minimum).|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


AT|

^C@2Vulnerability, position and form of scoring are important.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


AT|

^C@2The main purpose is that responder is "looking for game" and opener needs to say if he is BAD (minimum) or GOOD.|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


AT|

^C@2A secondary purpose is that the location of the feature could help responder to bid 3NT, or game/slam in a suit.|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


AT|

^C@22NT then 3NT by responder offers opener the choice to correct back to 4 of the major (with unusual shape). Responder's direct 3NT response is not correctable.|
PG| ***** 63 ***** |


AT|

^C@2Discuss opener's 4-level jump rebid after 2NT (my recommendation: A side 5-card suit, so 6-5).|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


AT| 

^C@2Be sure you know if a new suit is forcing after a weak two-bid (standard is "YES").|
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


AT|

^C@2Also learn the LAW of Total Tricks for responding to preempts. If no Game Interest, Follow the LAW.|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


AT|

The 2NT ask and opener's answer are alertable.|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


